<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/78308CAA-8483-45C0-A280-0AB4B6AD9D35"><gtr:id>78308CAA-8483-45C0-A280-0AB4B6AD9D35</gtr:id><gtr:name>Medical Research Council</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Polaris House</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>North Star Avenue</gtr:line2><gtr:postCode>SN2 1FL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South West</gtr:region></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/78308CAA-8483-45C0-A280-0AB4B6AD9D35"><gtr:id>78308CAA-8483-45C0-A280-0AB4B6AD9D35</gtr:id><gtr:name>Medical Research Council</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Polaris House</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>North Star Avenue</gtr:line2><gtr:postCode>SN2 1FL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South West</gtr:region></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/617C3C31-816B-4F3F-ADBE-5B20C334D3E6"><gtr:id>617C3C31-816B-4F3F-ADBE-5B20C334D3E6</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Peter</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>MacCallum</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_U122785830"><gtr:id>7F60BEE3-1C08-4209-AA69-627E75ECC202</gtr:id><gtr:title>Air Travel and VTE main study (DVT-MAIN)</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_U122785830</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>There is need to better estimate the risk of blood clots in the veins cause by air travel. This remains uncertain despite much media publicity. We wish to identify through 1240 people registered with general practices who have had a diagnosis of a blood clot within the past year (cases) together with four times that number of people of the same age and sex but who have not had a blood clot (control). Cases and controls would fill in a questionnaire asking details about travel and other risk factors for blood clots. By comparing the two groups the association of air travel with blood clots would be estimated.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>The association of air travel with venous thromboembolism (VTE) is a subject of considerable uncertainty despite current media interest. Recent reviews recognize the need for better epidemiological evidence to inform public debate. To date there have been four case-control studies. Two of these described positive associations with travel and DVT and the fourth study found no overall evidence of an association of air travel with DVT unless other risk factors were present. All four studies have methodological flaws and none of them were sufficiently powered to establish an association between air travel and VTE.||The aim of this study to quantify the size of risk of VTE associated with air travel using a case control methodology. It involves identification of 1240 cases of VTE occurring within the past year matched with four age and sex-matched controls that have not had a VTE. These population-based controls will be properly selected from General Practice registers, resolving a key methodological issue that has been a weakness of other studies. Cases and controls will be sent a questionnaire asking details about travel history and other risk factors. Questionnaires will be returned to the co-ordinating centre where the data will be entered and analysed. In a number of practices a more detailed questionnaire will be piloted to enable a more detailed study of travel related risk factors for VTE.||This research is funded by the British Heart Foundation and is a collaboration between GPRF and Queen Marys and Westfield College.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>89942</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4C9D7CAA-0686-4C29-B4A9-B503A42A5C50</gtr:id><gtr:title>Cumulative flying time and risk of venous thromboembolism.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>British journal of haematology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/eb4c1fc2e2de335a545672ebe596d5d3"><gtr:id>eb4c1fc2e2de335a545672ebe596d5d3</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>MacCallum PK</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0007-1048</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>qaZQeJLg6R3</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">MC_U122785830</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories><gtr:healthCategory><gtr:id>939798CA-B6AE-4C12-9DCC-A0F88F84E6F3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Blood</gtr:text></gtr:healthCategory></gtr:healthCategories><gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchActivity><gtr:id>FB395309-E202-4FE8-87B0-041A3D72D4D4</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>2.5  Research design and methodologies (aetiology)</gtr:text></gtr:researchActivity></gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchSubjects/><gtr:researchTopics/><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gt